  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These set global standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) practices\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases\n- Sharing evidence and legal resources across borders\n- Extradition agreements for financial criminals\n\n3. Reporting and Information Sharing\n- Banks and financial institutions required to report suspicious transactions\n- International databases and information exchange platforms\n- Collaborative efforts to track cross-border financial activities\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries align their domestic laws with international standards\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Similar enforcement mechanisms and legal frameworks\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International sanctions against countries with weak AML regulations\n- Coordinated efforts to combat financial crimes\n- Pressure on nations to implement robust anti-money laundering systems\n\n6. Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)\n- National agencies that collect and analyze financial transaction reports\n- Collaborate internationally to investigate suspicious activities\n\nThese intersections create a complex global system for preventing and prosecuting money laundering.",
